<div id="review_1636260331" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1636260331" />
    <a title="Howard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5928275-howard"><img alt="Howard" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1636260331?book_show_action=true">May 12, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Howard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Howard" href="/user/show/5928275-howard">Howard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780199535613" href="/book/show/2430644.Candide_and_Other_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5928275-howard?shelf=naughty-classic">naughty-classic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1636260331" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15783841259252770562">This is a wonderful collection of short stories including the famous Candide first published in 1759. I did not know what to expect of Candide or indeed anything from Voltaire; but I found Candide an immensely funny and clever tale. I now gather that it has been highly regarded since it was written (except of course the Catholic Church that banned it at the time for its insightful arguments against religious ideas and doctrines). The turn of phrase is skilfully funny and pithy. Candide is a Germ</span>
  <span id="freeText15783841259252770562" style="display:none">This is a wonderful collection of short stories including the famous Candide first published in 1759. I did not know what to expect of Candide or indeed anything from Voltaire; but I found Candide an immensely funny and clever tale. I now gather that it has been highly regarded since it was written (except of course the Catholic Church that banned it at the time for its insightful arguments against religious ideas and doctrines). The turn of phrase is skilfully funny and pithy. Candide is a German Quixote type character battling fate and ‘the best of all worlds’ as he avoids the vagaries of war, politics, wealth and life.<br /><br />The other short stories are all a good set of philosophical tales; in similar style but having modern ‘Enlightment’ ideas. The other stories include ‘Micromegas’ a story about a galactic traveller arriving on earth and trying to understand the microbes (humans); ‘Zadig’ is about Zoroastrian type Persian and court dealing; ‘What pleases the ladies’ is a poem about a knight being tricked into marrying a hag; ‘The Ingenu’ tells of a native Canadian finding his way to the French bourgeoisie and falling in love (a bit like the ‘Good Soldier Svejk’) and ‘the White Bull’ is a Metamorphosis Greek like fable of a lover being turned into a bull.<br /><br />Candide is outstanding and worth reading, as indeed are the others in the collection too.<br /><br />Lots of brilliant quotes in such a short book but here are a few:<br /><br />“She caught a glimpse through the bushes of Dr Pangloss a giving lesson in applied physiology to her mother’s maid, a very pretty and very receptive little brunette. As Miss Cunegonde had quite a gift for science, she noted in breathless silence the repeated experiments to which she was witness”<br /><br />“I have seen mortals who are considerably inferior to us, and I have seen some who are considerably superior. But I have never seen any one who did not have more desires than they had real needs, and more needs than they had possibilities of satisfaction.”<br /><br />“O God, who has given intelligence to forms of matter which seem so negligible, the infinitesimally small costs you as little as the infinitely large”<br /><br />(One for us English – Voltaire spent time here) “There you are, that’s typical of the damned English… they care more about Shakespeare’s plays, and plum pudding, and bottles of rum, than they do about the Pentateuch”<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15783841259252770562" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

