<div id="review_3806813705" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3806813705" />
    <a title="Marc Sebastian Head" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/128635665-marc-sebastian-head"><img alt="Marc Sebastian Head" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614076401p2/128635665.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3806813705?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marc Sebastian Head" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marc Sebastian Head" href="/user/show/128635665-marc-sebastian-head">Marc Sebastian Head</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780192834263" href="/book/show/77715.Candide_and_Other_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3806813705" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3567112059727024840">This is a hard one to rate as it is a collection of shorter stories, and I had only intended to read Candide, but I enjoyed it so much I read the others too, and it felt disingenuous to rate them individually. <br/><br/>I thoroughly enjoyed most of these - whether it is the abiding talent of Voltaire or credit due the translator, the stories still zing with life and wit. They are somewhat variations on a theme, which is a bit of a shame, but overall I am delighted to find that Voltaire held up to his repu</span>
  <span id="freeText3567112059727024840" style="display:none">This is a hard one to rate as it is a collection of shorter stories, and I had only intended to read Candide, but I enjoyed it so much I read the others too, and it felt disingenuous to rate them individually. <br /><br />I thoroughly enjoyed most of these - whether it is the abiding talent of Voltaire or credit due the translator, the stories still zing with life and wit. They are somewhat variations on a theme, which is a bit of a shame, but overall I am delighted to find that Voltaire held up to his reputation. I'm not going to waste my time reviewing him, but some impressions of the individual stories are below:<br /><br />Candide: absolutely brilliant, somewhat picaresque and darkly humourous. I'll leave the philosophy for others to expound, but an interesting reflection on the darkness of society while still being a rip-roaring adventure reminiscent of Verne and Swift. I would happily read this one again.<br /><br />Micromegas: shocked when I started reading - 'is this Sci Fi??' Plays with the idea of scale, very huge alien visitors reveal just how small (and petty) we can be. Encourages us to broaden our horizons, which I felt applied scientifically and spiritually.<br /><br />Zadig: actually, I think I enjoyed this more than Candide! Got some distinct Sherlock vibes at first (by way of the Arabian Nights), then becomes a broader tale essentially proving that 'no good deed goes unpunished', with perhaps some reflections on why. Zadig as a character less flighty or naive than Candide.<br /><br />Ingenu: using the idea of 'The Noble Savage', explores the contradictions in society and how far some structures and dogmas of organised religion have strayed from what is actually contained in the Bible. Uses the eyes of an outsider to cheekily lampoon his society.<br /><br />The White Bull: didn't really resonate with me, odd but fun mix of The Old Testament and Ovid. Not sure I really 'got it', and wasn't invested enough in this one to try and find out.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3567112059727024840" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


